nodes.bodyText:
Instead of doing this as an abstract class, and requiring someone to extend it, I suggest to use the "observer" design pattern. If you do that, this class would become a final class, and would provide a way to be "observed."
A classic Java implementation of this would be like:
final class ApplicationForegroundTracker {
    private final Set<Observer> observers;

    ApplicationForegroundTracker() {
        this.observers = new HashSet<>();
    }

    void registerForegroundObserver(Observer observer) {
        synchronized (observers) {
            this.observers.add(ObjectsCompat.requireNonNull(observer));
        }
    }

    void unregisterForegroundObserver(Observer observer) {
        synchronized (observers) {
            observers.remove(Objects.requireNonNull(observer));
        }
    }

    // Somewhere in your code, when its time to notify that you have a new state ...
    // You can call this either like notify(observer::onApplicationEnteredForeground);
    // or like notify(observer::onApplicationEnteredBackground);
    void notify(NotificationStrategy strategy) {
        Set<Observer> threadSafeObserversCopy = new HashSet<>();
        synchronized (observers) {
            threadSafeObserversCopy.addAll(observers);
        }

        for (Observer observer: threadSafeObserversCopy) {
            strategy.apply(observer);
        }      
    }

    interface Observer {
        void onApplicationEnteredForeground();
        void onApplciationEnteredBackground();
    }

    // An internal interface to define a function which calls back an observer.
    // This is a strategy design pattern. One strategy might be to call 
    // {@link Observer#onApplicationEnteredForeground()}. Another strategy might be
    // to call {@link Observer#onAppliactionEnteredBackground()}.
    // This strategy is used to execute a small bit of code inside of the notification routine,
    // where a lot of the same setup is used regardless of the notification strategy.
    interface NotificationStrategy {
        void apply(Observer observer);
    }
}

Anyway, then you'd use it like:
final ApplicationForegroundTracker tracker = new AppliactionForegroundTracker();
final ApplicationForegroundTracker.Observer observer = new ApplicationForegroundTracker.Observer() {
    @Override public void onApplicationEnteredForeground() {
        analyticsSession.resume(); // or whatever
    }
    @Overridd public void onApplicactionEnteredBackground() {
        analyticsSession.pause(); // or whatever
    }
};

tracker.addForegroundObserver(observer);
...
tracker.removeForegroundObserver(observer);

